  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue: The issue occurs when the globalopt pass transforms a pointer global variable that is initialized to null and
has atomic stores/loads into a boolean tracking variable (@g.init). The transformation creates atomic operations on an i1 type, which violates LLVM's
requirement that atomic memory accesses must be at least byte-sized (8 bits). The verifier correctly identifies this as invalid IR and aborts.\n\n2.
Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that after transformation, we have:\n```\nstore atomic i1 true, ptr @g.init seq_cst, align 1\n%g.init.val = load atomic
i1, ptr @g.init seq_cst, align 1\n```\nBoth operations are on i1 type with atomic ordering, which triggers the verifier error \"atomic memory access' size
must be byte-sized\" because i1 is only 1 bit, not 8 bits or more.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: In GlobalOpt.cpp, the function
`OptimizeGlobalAddressOfAllocation` creates a boolean tracking global (`InitBool`) for pointer globals that are initialized to null. When processing atomic
stores and loads to the original global, it preserves the atomic ordering by passing `SI->getOrdering()` and `SI->getSyncScopeID()` to the new store/load
instructions on the boolean global. However, since the boolean global has i1 type (1 bit), these atomic operations become invalid according to LLVM's atomic
memory access requirements, which mandate that atomic operations must be on types that are at least 8 bits in size and power-of-two sized.\n\n4. Proposed
Edit Point(s):\n+ Lines 968-972 in llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp: When creating the new store instruction for the InitBool, we need to check if the
original store was atomic. If it was, we cannot safely create an atomic store to an i1 type. Instead, we should either skip the optimization for atomic cases
or use a non-atomic store (since the boolean tracking variable doesn't require atomic semantics for correctness in this context).\n+ Lines 988-991 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp: Similarly, when creating the load instruction for the InitBool, we need to handle the case where the original load was
atomic. We should create a non-atomic load instead of preserving the atomic ordering.\n\nThe fix is to avoid creating atomic operations on i1 types by using
non-atomic operations for the boolean tracking variable, since the boolean is only used for local optimization purposes and doesn't require the same atomic
semantics as the original pointer global.\n\n5. Conclusion: By modifying the code to create non-atomic store and load instructions for the boolean tracking
variable regardless of the original atomic ordering, we prevent the creation of invalid IR with atomic operations on sub-byte types. This maintains the
correctness of the optimization while ensuring the generated IR passes verification.",
